cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.NA, cs.SI. 

The paper deals with constructing a plane spanner of a complete Euclidean graph, which is a problem in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves algorithms and data structures, which suggests cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as another likely sub-category. The use of Delaunay triangulations and equilateral-triangle distance suggests cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) as a possible sub-category. The stretch factor and distance metrics used in the paper also suggest cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as possible sub-categories.
